Here is an example of how you can generate a chessboard in LaTeX using FEN notation:

\begin{code}
\documentclass[12pt, a4paper]{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{graphicx}
\usepackage{chess}
\begin{document}
\begin{chessboard}[fen=\(FEN_STRING\)]{8}{8}
  \foreach \i in {1,...,8} { \foreach \j in {1,...,8} {\put{\ifthenelse{\i=\j}{\textcolor{red}{\chesspiece[FCH]}}{}}{}} }
\end{chessboard}
\end{document}
\end{code}

The `fen` argument of the `\chessboard` command takes the FEN string as input, which is what you need to generate your chessboard in FEN notation. You can substitute the `FEN_STRING` with the actual FEN string generated from your scacchiere.  You can then use the `\ifthenelse` command to color the squares as needed based on the FEN string.

In this example, I have used a simple loop to draw all the squares on a chessboard. You can replace this with whatever code you need to generate your scacchiere. You can also use the `\put` command with a chess piece symbol instead of using the `\ifthenelse` command.  Finally, you will need to add any other required packages or commands as needed for your particular setup.

